{"course_name": "Topics in Italian Lit:", "description": "", "classification": "ITAL-GA", "grading": "GSAS Graded", "class_name": "Italian Literary Obscene", "meet_data": "[{'start': '9.30 AM', 'end': '12.15 PM', 'day': 'Thu'}]", "notes": "Course Repeatable for Credit.  \n\r  This course considers the aesthetics of the obscene in literary texts from the late nineteenth century to the present. We will read novels that include graphic depictions of sex acts and reproductive organs, as well as essays and treatises that use similarly vivid attention to bodies to reflect on representation and set out a literary dogma. \nMindful of a tradition endemic to Western literature and philosophy that figures the denuded body as a locus of unveiled truth, we will ask: what does it mean for a text to present itself as always already exposed? What hermeneutic approaches do such texts solicit and/or thwart? Our consideration of these questions will engage with psychoanalytic theories of repression and sublimation, but also with Michel Foucault\u2019s critique of the \u201crepressive hypothesis\u201d in The History of Sexuality. Do these texts enjoy what Foucault calls the speaker\u2019s benefit: the deliberate appearance of transgression that is inherent to discussing what is repressed? \nWe will ask these questions of a variety of modern and contemporary literary texts, moving in roughly chronological order from decadent, positivist, futurist, and neo-avantgardist writings to texts by Gadda, Moravia, Pasolini, Ferrante, and Tondelli.  \n\nTexts include Gabriele d\u2019Annunzio, Il piacere; Elena Ferrante, I giorni dell\u2019abbandono; Carlo Emilio Gadda, Eros e Priapo; Luigi Malerba, Il protagonista; Giorgio Manganelli, Hilarotragoedia; Paolo Mantegazza, Fisiologia dell\u2019amore; F. T. Marinetti, Mafarka le futuriste; Alberto Moravia, Io e lui; Giovanni Papini, \u201cIl massacro delle donne\u201d; Pier Paolo Pasolini, Petrolio (selections); Pitigrilli, Cocaine; Italo Tavolato, \u201cContro la morale sessuale\u201d; Pier Vittorio Tondelli, Altri libertini; and essays by Giorgio Agamben, Guido Almansi, Carmelo Bene, Jacques Derrida, Gilles Deleuze, Teresa de Lauretis, Roberto Esposito, Dario Fo, Michel Foucault, Sigmund Freud, Lynn Hunt, Jacques Lacan, Thomas Laqueur, Pasolini, Linda Williams. \n\nClass conducted in English; Reading proficiency in Italian required.", "instructors": ["Falkoff, Rebecca Ruth"], "component": "Seminar", "number": "2192", "loc_code": "WS", "session": {"start": "09/02/2014", "end": "12/12/2014", "day": ""}, "college": "Graduate School of Arts and Science", "location": "CASA 201", "units": "4", "is_open": true, "section": "001"}
