{"course_name": "Tpcs in Italian-American Culture", "description": "", "classification": "ITAL-GA", "grading": "GSAS Graded", "class_name": "Discovering Sensory Intelligence", "meet_data": "[{'start': '3.30 PM', 'end': '6.10 PM', 'day': 'Thu'}]", "notes": "Discovering the Sensory Intelligence of Italians Worldwide seeks to pose a simple question: how does the mind of an immigrant work? The mind of an immigrant is not, of course, intrinsically different from that of a more sedentary individual; nevertheless his/her language, emotional bent, visual perception are profoundly affected by the life-changing move. It is crucial, then, that we devote our attention, in class, to documents and testimonies that allow us to get as near as possible to the contents and feelings of a personal experience. We will look, through a number of evidences, at how his/her senses and logic react to and work in a totally new environment, and how in turn a new world affects the immigrant\u2019s psychology and behavior. We will look at a variety of sources, from different realms of human expression, and at the same time we will expand our geographical approach, considering the Italian immigrant experience in the U.S. and beyond in a more global perspective. In recent years, groundbreaking work like that of David Gerber and Camilla Cattarulla has shown the necessity of making room, in scholarly research, for a more empathic consideration of the immigrants\u2019 narratives, which very often deal with personal matters.", "instructors": [], "component": "Seminar", "number": "2165", "loc_code": "WS", "session": {"start": "09/02/2014", "end": "12/12/2014", "day": ""}, "college": "Graduate School of Arts and Science", "location": "CASA 201", "units": "4", "is_open": true, "section": "001"}
